JbxnAH6P3wKgbQFffQKB49RESnaAzBJtz2iUrfmIoiIutnhXsTzplJbBcCMjfst2Onmul2wdeDeY-hvH-EPY-umxblomjpdQqffz3VjmZkzCVM_VLfexfIWWaiuAw7-hhMcRT49w1QpO8hcmR0VqFuzaJFtwWZwA-Qo-gv_i0sYuY1tMchvgmvBf2OpbJz692SLp9Hm03ClWah9cFvWst-Z0BADsL29J6Mz51ruWDJFholKgLHJyCNDSH8SjyQli4kUuW_cDghOtnPztTFOGAOSr8iSLHfus1S8FwE4gWfKWdBT0YYheDAhCJncALYyHleMTubqb-tQttmP1O0i5EBH2bzitO22OroYCZUAG_YA6RQO1ctMErU8Dy4IbBikBoy_HQTvS0vFCHgrfPn8sk2q8J7W9P8nNjWxu96Ra\\\",\\\"summary\\\":[{\\\"type\\\":\\\"summary_text\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"**Considering test refinement**\\\\n\\\\nI’m thinking about the need to refine tests after the prompt to “Add or refine tests.” Adding explicit assertions post-signature seems essential. Should I include comments? Maybe. A \\\\\\\"public API proof\\\\\\\" test could also be useful to trigger the constructor without the full SSH setup, ensuring it doesn’t throw errors. Avoiding dynamic KeyPair generation by using embedded keys could streamline our focus on the active class and enhance speed. However, I wonder if generating sample keys would still be acceptable.\\\"},{\\\"type\\\":\\\"summary_text\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"**Exploring test options**\\\\n\\\\nI could consider writing code using Java generation and DER methods, but the current KeyPair approach is simpler. I’m wondering if keeping the class dynamic is necessary, especially since KeyPair introduces dynamic access, which might not be required. I know I need a \\\\\\\"one-to-one mapping\\\\\\\" class for IdentityFileTest. It might be helpful to look for old tests in upstream, but they're not essential. Adding stronger assertions could be beneficial, though I'm concerned about coverage, especially since current tests might not run after adding a signature parse.\\\"},{\\\"type\\\":\\\"summary_text\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"**Considering test updates**\\\\n\\\\nI’m thinking it might help to add a comment in the test to clarify some things, although it might not be necessary. I could update the test so it not only throws an IOExcep